<body>

    <h1>Project Workflow: AI-Powered Insider Threat Detection System</h1>

    <div class="highlight">
        <p><strong>Project Name:</strong> ThreatGuard.AI Security Intelligence Platform</p>
        <p><strong>Tech Stack:</strong> Python, Flask, SQLAlchemy, Scikit-Learn (Isolation Forest), Bootstrap 5, Chart.js</p>
    </div>

    <h2>1. System Architecture Overview</h2>
    <p>The system is designed following the MVC (Model-View-Controller) architecture pattern. It continuously monitors user activities, evaluates them using Machine Learning models, and dynamically adjusts user risk scores to trigger threat alerts.</p>

    <h3>1.1. The Frontend (View Layer)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Built using HTML5, CSS3, and JavaScript.</li>
        <li>Utilizes Bootstrap 5 for responsive layout and a custom dark glassmorphism cyber-theme.</li>
        <li>Features interactive charts using <strong>Chart.js</strong> on the Dashboard and Risk Analysis pages.</li>
        <li>The landing page includes custom HTML5 Canvas particle effects, 3D CSS animations, and seamless routing to the authentication portal.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1.2. The Backend (Controller Layer)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Powered by <strong>Flask</strong>, utilizing Blueprints to organize routes modularly (e.g., <code>auth_routes</code>, <code>dashboard_routes</code>, <code>risk_routes</code>, etc.).</li>
        <li>Handles session management and authentication using <strong>Flask-Login</strong>.</li>
        <li>Processes frontend requests and communicates with the Services and AI layers.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>1.3. The Database (Model Layer)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Uses <strong>SQLite</strong> with <strong>SQLAlchemy ORM</strong>.</li>
        <li>Maintains four primary models:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>User:</strong> Stores employee credentials and roles.</li>
                <li><strong>ActivityLog:</strong> Tracks specific actions (files accessed, USB usage, failed logins).</li>
                <li><strong>RiskScore:</strong> Maintains the dynamic risk level (Low, Medium, High) of each user.</li>
                <li><strong>ThreatAlert:</strong> Stores triggered alerts with severity levels for the admin to review.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. Core Workflow & AI Detection Logic</h2>
    
    <h3>Phase 1: Data Ingestion</h3>
    <p>As users interact with the company's network (simulated through the application), their actions such as the number of files accessed, USB drives mounted, and failed login attempts are logged into the <code>ActivityLog</code> database.</p>

    <h3>Phase 2: AI Anomaly Detection</h3>
    <p>The <code>ai_service.py</code> feeds the new activity data as a Pandas DataFrame into the <code>ai_engine.py</code>.</p>
    <p>The engine uses the <strong>Scikit-Learn Isolation Forest</strong> algorithm. This is an unsupervised machine learning model that specializes in identifying anomalies (outliers) in high-dimensional data. If the model outputs a <code>-1</code>, the behavior is flagged as anomalous.</p>

    <h3>Phase 3: Risk Scoring & Alert Generation</h3>
    <p>If an anomaly is detected, the <code>risk_service.py</code> is triggered. It adds points to the user's risk score in the database.</p>
    <p>Based on the new score, the system dynamically recalculates the user's Risk Level:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>0 - 30:</strong> Low Risk</li>
        <li><strong>31 - 70:</strong> Medium Risk</li>
        <li><strong>71 - 100:</strong> High Risk</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If the score crosses a certain threshold or a critical anomaly occurs, a new <code>ThreatAlert</code> is generated.</p>

    <h3>Phase 4: Admin Dashboard & Reporting</h3>
    <p>The Cybersecurity Admin logs into the portal and views real-time data populated by the Flask routes. They can monitor High-Risk Users, view the Threat Trend charts, and download PDF/CSV compliance reports generated by the <code>report_service.py</code>.</p>

</body>
